132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 14
S.P. 27 In Senate, January 8, 2025
An Act to Provide Indigenous Peoples Free Access to State Parks
Received by the Secretary of the Senate on January 6, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed.
DAREK M. GRANT
Secretary of the Senate
Presented by Senator HICKMAN of Kennebec.
Cosponsored by Representative HASENFUS of Readfield and
Senators: BAILEY of York, BENNETT of Oxford, TIPPING of Penobscot, Representative:
Speaker FECTEAU of Biddeford.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 12 MRSA §1819-C is enacted to read:
3 §1819-C. Free admission for members of federally recognized Indian nation, tribe or
4 band
5 Notwithstanding section 1819, a member of a federally recognized Indian nation, tribe
6 or band in this State is not required to pay a fee for admission to any state-owned park,
7 historic site, camping area or beach managed by the State. To qualify for free admission
8 under this section, a person shall present a qualifying tribal identification, as approved by
9 the respective tribal government, to the bureau staff on duty or other designee of the
10 director.
11 SUMMARY
1122 This bill provides that a member of a federally recognized Indian nation, tribe or band
1133 in Maine is not required to pay a fee for admission to any state-owned park, historic site,
1144 camping area or beach managed by the State. The bill also specifies that to qualify for free
1155 admission, a person is required to present a qualifying tribal identification, as approved by
1166 the respective tribal government, to the park attendant or other designee of the Director of
1177 the Bureau of Parks and Lands within the Department of Agriculture, Conservation and
1188 Forestry.
